  "texts": [
    "Dynamic Rank Allocation: DRaFT-Q monitors loss or gradient-based signals using exponential moving averages (EMAs) and adjusts the adapter rank per layer on-the-fly.",
    "This enables the model to allocate higher capacity to difficult layers and reduce it where unnecessary, optimizing parameter use and VRAM footprint during training.2.",
    "Reward-Weighted Loss: DRaFT-Q integrates token-level reward signals into the loss function, upweighting semantically important tokens (e.g., final answers or reasoning-critical spans).",
    "This focuses gradient updates on key information, improving reasoning quality without modifying model architecture or requiring reinforcement learning.We evaluate DRaFT-Q on multiple reasoning benchmarks-CommonsenseQA, OpenBookQA, GSM8K, and OpenAssistant-using LLaMA-2 models in 4-bit quantized form.",
    "All 7B experiments were conducted on single NVIDIA T4 GPUs, while 13B-scale experiments used L40-class hardware."
  ],
